Title: Absorption cross section of a Schwarzschild black hole for a massive vector field
Authors: Kaustubh Mukund Vispute, Rajesh Karmakar
arXiv: https://arxiv.org/abs/2606.13217 [gr-qc, hep-th]
What the Post Is Showing
The post is sharing a new research paper that calculates how a massive vector field (think of it as a massive version of the electromagnetic field, sometimes called a Proca field) is absorbed by a Schwarzschild black hole.
The attached image is likely a graph showing the absorption cross-section — essentially how “big” the black hole appears to this type of field at different frequencies or masses.
Simple Explanation
In standard physics:
A normal (massless) photon has a well-known absorption behavior when falling into a black hole.
When the field has mass, its behavior changes. It can no longer travel at the speed of light, and its wave nature is modified.
The paper calculates how much of this massive field gets swallowed by the black hole versus how much is scattered.
This is a technical calculation in General Relativity + Quantum Field Theory on curved spacetime. It helps physicists understand how different types of fields (not just light) interact with black holes — which is useful for studying things like dark matter candidates, modified gravity, and the behavior of fields near horizons.
